To represent the path of a single photon of light traveling from the Sun to Earth in LaTeX, we can illustrate it as a straight line since light travels in a straight path in a vacuum. Here's a simple representation:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
    % Sun
    \filldraw[orange] (0,0) circle (1cm) node[anchor=east] {Sun};

    % Earth
    \filldraw[blue] (10,0) circle (0.5cm) node[anchor=west] {Earth};

    % Path of the photon
    \draw[->, thick] (1,0) -- (9.5,0) node[midway, above] {Photon path};

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

To calculate the time it takes for a photon to travel from the Sun to Earth, we can use the following formula:

\[
t = \frac{d}{c}
\]

Where:
- \( t \) is the time taken,
- \( d \) is the distance from the Sun to Earth,
- \( c \) is the speed of light in a vacuum.

The average distance from the Sun to Earth is approximately \( 149.6 \times 10^6 \) kilometers, and the speed of light \( c \) is \( 299,792 \) kilometers per second. Plugging these values into the formula gives:

\[
t = \frac{149.6 \times 10^6 \text{ km}}{299,792 \text{ km/s}}
\]

Calculating this gives:

\[
t \approx 499 \text{ seconds}
\]

Thus, it takes approximately 499 seconds or about 8 minutes and 19 seconds for a photon to travel from the Sun to Earth.
